{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"100af41f-3753-4b9c-be2c-6e2b58dee851","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.0 switched the default test runner from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform.**\n\nIn 3.x, the SDK defaulted to the VSTest infrastructure, so `vstest.console` could discover and run tests normally. Starting with 4.0, the default is the newer **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** runner, which produces a standalone executable that `vstest.console` doesn't understand.\n\n### Fixes (pick one):\n\n1. **Opt back into VSTest** — add to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n2. **Switch CI to `dotnet test`** — it works with both runners. For the new platform, also add:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n3. **Run the test executable directly** — the built output is a self-contained test app:\n   ```bash\n   ./YourTestProject --list-tests   # discover\n   ./YourTestProject                # run\n   ```\n\nOption 2 is the recommended path forward since Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the actively invested runner.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7e0a05b5-ddfe-4a5c-a0d3-92195c59664d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change between MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0 and MSTest.Sdk/4.1.0 regarding test discovery with vstest.console. This is a knowledge question about MSTest SDK changes, not a code task. Let me answer from my knowledge.\n\nIn MSTest.Sdk 4.0+, the default test runner changed. MSTest.Sdk 3.x defaulted to VSTest as the runner, but starting with MSTest.Sdk 4.0, the default runner is Microsoft.Testing.Platform (the new \"native\" runner). This means the generated test executable is a standalone executable that doesn't use vstest.console for discovery/execution.\n \nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform as the runner, vstest.console can't discover or run tests anymore since the test assembly is now a self-contained app rather than a VSTest-compatible adapter. To fix this, you can either enable dotnet test integration with a project property, switch back to the VSTest runner, or update your CI to use dotnet test or run the executable directly.","outputTokens":633,"requestId":"BD0C:93C8B:1F84D03:23CC23C:6A07D61A"},"id":"e5e68c79-2c01-4804-8762-fd7873f8e706","timestamp":"2026-05-16T02:27:52.752Z","parentId":"03a31403-2df5-4f44-9c29-a5213297ee94"}
